==Deceased people== ===Jeanetta Thomas=== '''J(e)anetta Jane Thomas''' (2 December 1869 â 5 January 1982)<ref name="Supercentenarians who lived in the United Kingdom"/> of [[Llantrisant]], Wales was a British [[supercentenarian]] and was mentioned in the [[Guinness Book of Records]] in the 1980s. Thomas spent her youth in London working as a [[seamstress]]. At the age of around 40, she returned to Wales to open a [[drapery]] shop, which she ran until the age of 98.<ref name="thomas1982guardian">{{cite news|title=Oldest woman dies aged 112|pages=1|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=7 January 1982|accessdate=2009-01-27}}</ref> Thomas was the last surviving person in the UK to have been born in the 1860s. She was also the oldest living person in the United Kingdom from 20 October 1980 until her death, at the age of 112 years and 34 days. She was the last surviving person in Britain to be born in the [[1860s]].
From the age of 107, Thomas resided at a nursing home at [[Cowbridge]], Wales.<ref name="thomas1982guardian"/> A photograph of her, which was taken the day before her 112th birthday, appeared in [[The Times]]. Had Thomas lived another six days, she would have broken the British longevity record which at that time was held by [[Alice Stevenson]]. Thomas still holds the record for the oldest Welsh-born woman ever, although Welshman [[John Evans (supercentenarian)|John Evans]] and English-born [[Anna Eliza Williams]] (who died in Wales) both lived longer.
{{S-start}} {{Succession box | before = Florence Pannell | title = [[#Chronological list of the oldest living person in the United Kingdom since 1963|United Kingdom's oldest recognised living person]] | years = 20 October 1980 â 5 January 1982 | after = Alice Brewster }} {{S-end}}
===Daisy Adams=== '''Daisy Irene Adams''' (nÃ©e '''Woodward'''; 30 June 1880 &ndash; 8 December 1993) was for about nine months the oldest person in the UK, between 17 March 1993 and her death on 8 December 1993. She was from [[Church Gresley]], [[Derbyshire]]. She died at the age of 113 years and 161 days, and outlived her husband and three of her five children. Her husband died at the first day of the [[Battle of the Somme]]. Adams was a [[teetotal]]er and ate little. Her son Ted put her longevity down to "living a quiet life".<ref name="AdamsTimes">{{cite news |title=Oldest Briton dies |work=The Times |date=9 December 1993 |accessdate=2009-09-29}}</ref><ref name="AdamsDMail">{{cite news |title=Women born before the motor car |work=Daily Mail |date=9 December 1993 |accessdate=2009-09-29}}</ref>
{{s-start}} {{succession box | before = [[Charlotte Hughes (supercentenarian)|Charlotte Hughes]] | title = [[#Chronological list of the oldest living person in the United Kingdom since 1963|United Kingdom's oldest recognised living person]] | years = 17 March 1993 &ndash; 8 December 1993 | after = [[List of British supercentenarians#Rebecca Hewison|Rebecca Hewison]] }} {{s-end}}
===Rebecca Hewison=== Rebecca Hewison (nÃ©e '''Ramsdale'''; 19 October 1881 &ndash; 22 September 1994) was a British supercentenarian and the oldest person living in Britain until her death aged 112 years, 338 days. Born in [[Grimsby]], Hewison was the fourth child of six born to Will, a timber merchant, and Betsy-Ann Ramsdale. She married George Hewison, a [[stonemason]], in Grimsby in 1905. In 1938 she moved to be with her daughter Frances in North London. Later in 1963 the family moved to [[Berrynarbor]] in [[Devon]] until Hewison was 105 when she returned to her hometown of Grimsby. In 1990 she met the [[Queen Mother]] at [[RAF Scampton]]. She also was a supporter of [[Grimsby Town]] football club and met the team in 1991, the year she turned 100 and also the year that the team completed a second successive promotion. Hewison was also taken for flights in [[aeroplane]]s and [[helicopter]]s at [[Humberside Airport]]. She had enjoyed music since a young child and attributed her longevity to the occasional glass of lemon and port.<ref name="HewisonDMail">{{cite news |title=Rebecca: the story of a quiet life that spanned 112 years; born the year Billy the Kid died, she was Britain's oldest person |work=Daily Mail |date=24 September 1994 |accessdate=2009-09-29}}</ref>
{{s-start}} {{succession box | before = [[List of British supercentenarians#Daisy Adams|Daisy Adams]] | title = [[#Chronological list of the oldest living person in the United Kingdom since 1963|United Kingdom's oldest recognised living person]] | years = 8 December 1993 &ndash; 22 September 1994 | after = Annie Scott }} {{s-end}}
===Lucy Jane Askew=== '''Lucy Jane Askew''' (8 September 1883 &ndash; 9 December 1997) was an English [[supercentenarian]] and the [[List of European supercentenarians|oldest person in Europe]] at the time of her death at the age of [[list of the verified oldest people|114 years and 92 days]]. Askew was born and died in [[Loughton]], [[Essex]]. She was born to Arthur George Askew and Susan Elizabeth Askew nÃ©e Ellis, prosperous landowners. Lucy had five other siblings, all of whom she outlived, although three of them also lived past [[centenarian|100]]. Askew never married and was a devout [[Christian]]. Askew moved into a nursing home when she was 106 and survived a leg operation at 108. She was in good health until shortly before her death when she died peacefully in her sleep. She attributed her longevity to a modest lifestyle. Askew was the last person documented to have been born in 1883.<ref name="Askew">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/38373.stm|publisher=BBC News |title=Britain's oldest woman dies at 114 |date=10 December 1997|accessdate=2007-11-19}}</ref><ref name="AskewScotsman">{{cite news |title=Britain's oldest woman dies at 114 |work=The Scotsman |date=11 December 1997 |accessdate=2009-10-04}}</ref><ref name="AskewDMail">{{cite news |title=The woman who watched the world go by for 114 years |work=Daily Mail |date=11 December 1997 |accessdate=2009-10-04}}</ref> {{s-start}} {{succession box | before = AniÅ£ica Butariu | title = [[List of European supercentenarians#Chronological list of the oldest living person in Europe since 1947|Europe's oldest recognised living person]] | years = 21 November 1997 &ndash; 9 December 1997 | after = [[Annie Jennings]] }} {{succession box | before = Annie Scott | title = [[#Chronological list of the oldest living person in the United Kingdom since 1963|United Kingdom's oldest recognised living person]] | years = 21 April 1996 &ndash; 9 December 1997 | after = [[Annie Jennings]] }} {{s-end}}
===Louisa Shephard=== '''Louisa Shephard''' nÃ©e Williams (14 September 1898 &ndash; 19 January 2010) was, at the age of 111 years 127 days, a supercentenarian who became the last living person in Wales who was born in the 19th century and the [[Victorian Era]]. She became the second-oldest Welsh-born woman and the third-oldest person. She was also the third-oldest woman to die in Wales, and the fourth-oldest person. Therefore she was also the youngest Welsh supercentenarian and the only to die at age 111. At the time of her death, Shephard, of [[Blaenavon]], was the third oldest person in the United Kingdom, and the oldest person in [[Wales]] following the death on 9 May 2007 of Victoria May Owen, who was 109 years and 335 days. She was one of the fifty oldest British people. She attributed her longevity to "hot milk with a dash of whiskey each evening".<ref name="shephard1">{{cite news | last = Mlatem| first = Hannah| title = Louisa's tonic for a long life| publisher = [[South Wales Argus]]| date = 2006-09-14| url = http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/search/922057.Louisa_s_tonic_for_a_long_life/| accessdate = 2008-12-11}}</ref><ref name="shephard2">{{cite news | last = Crockett| first = Natalie| title = 110-year old could be Wales' oldest person| publisher = [[South Wales Argus]]| date = 2008-09-14| url = http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/search/3672838.110_year_old_could_be_Wales__oldest_woman/| accessdate = 2008-12-11}}</ref>
===Ethel Wood===
'''Ethel Eliza Wood''' (born 16 January 1901 at [[St Sampson, Guernsey]] &ndash; 19 August 2011)<ref name="GRG"/> from [[Kirby-le-Soken]], Essex was a British supercentenarian. At the age of {{age|1901|1|16}}, Wood was the ninth oldest verified person in the United Kingdom following the death of 112-year-old [[Margaret Fish]] on 12 March 2011. She was one of five children born to William and Lily Wood. Wood trained as a teacher in London prior to the German occupation of Guernsey. Like her siblings, she never married or had children. She moved to Essex in the 1990s to care for her younger sister, Edith. Wood lived in her own home until breaking her leg during a fall a month before her 110th birthday. She died suddenly on August 19th, 2011. If she had lived until December of that year, she would have surpased the only other supercententenarian from the [[Channel islands]], [[Margaret Ann Neve]] (1792 &ndash; 1903).[http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/essex_amazing_ethel_celebrates_her_110th_birthday_1_776944] [http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/localnews/4860901.Kirby__Ethel_celebrates_109th_birthday/]
==Living people== ===Violet Wood=== {{Main|Violet Wood}}
===Grace Jones=== {{Expand section|date=February 2011}} '''Grace Adelaide Jones''' (born 7 December 1899) of [[Bermondsey]], London, is an English [[supercentenarian]]. At the age of {{age|1899|12|7}}, Jones is the second oldest person in the United Kingdom following the death of 112-year-old [[Margaret Fish]] on 12 March 2011.<ref>http://www.southwarkweekender.co.uk/news/00,news,16842,440,00.htm</ref><ref>http://www.southlondon-today.co.uk/News.cfm?id=437</ref> She is also the youngest living person born in the 1800s.
===Ellen Watson=== '''Ellen Watson''' ([[nÃ©e]] '''Thorpe'''; born 3 January 1900) from [[Croydon]] is an English supercentenarian. At the age of {{age|1900|1|3}}, Watson is the third oldest person in the United Kingdom following the death of 112-year-old [[Margaret Fish]] on 12 March 2011, and also the oldest verified living person born in the 1900s.
In 1959, along with her spouse and daughter and daughter's husband, they moved to [[Staines]]. Then they moved to {{Disambiguation needed|Ashford|date=June 2011}} with Mrs Watson's two grandchildren, Janet and Jonathan.
Mrs. Watson lived there for three and a half decades. Also in 1974, the same house where she and her husband celebrated their golden wedding. Her husband Samuel died a few days later due to a long-term illness.
In the mid 1990s, Watson moved into a care home.
She credits her longevity to a healthy lifestyle and laughter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Great great grandmother turns 110 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/8437222.stm |publisher=BBC News|date=1 January 2010|accessdate=2010-06-11}}</ref>
===Ethel Lang=== {{Expand section|date=August 2010}} '''Ethel Lang''' (nÃ©e '''Lancaster'''; born 27 May 1900)<ref name="GRG"/> from [[Barnsley]], [[South Yorkshire]] is an English supercentenarian. At the age of {{age|1900|5|27}}, Lang is the fifth oldest verified person in the United Kingdom following the death of 111-year-old Gladys Good in October 2011. Lang was born at [[Worsbrough]], near Barnsley, to Charles and Sarah Lancaster and married William Lang in 1922. They had a daughter, Margaret, in 1923. Lang's mother lived to the age of 91 and her great-grandmother until 92.<ref name="lang108">{{cite news | title = Ethel in fine form at 108| publisher = The Star| date = 2008-06-02| url = http://www.thestar.co.uk/headlines/Ethel-in-fine-form-aged.4141452.jp| accessdate = 2010-08-17}}</ref><ref name="lang110">{{cite news | title = Ethel turns 110| publisher = Barnsley Town Talk| date = 2010-05-28| url = http://www.barnsley.towntalk.co.uk/news/d/14737/Ethel-Turns-100/| accessdate = 2010-08-17}}</ref>
===Margaret Cooke=== {{Expand section|date=February 2011}} '''Margaret Tugela Cooke''' (nÃ©e '''Butland'''; born 15 September 1900)<ref name="GRG"/> from [[Beaconsfield]], [[Buckinghamshire]] is an English supercentenarian. At the age of {{age|1900|9|15}}, Cooke is the sixth oldest verified person in the United Kingdom following the death of 111-year-old Gladys Good in October 2011. [http://beaconsfield.buckinghamshireadvertiser.co.uk/2008/09/beaconsfields-oldest-resident.html] [http://beaconsfield.buckinghamshireadvertiser.co.uk/2009/09/englands-fourth-oldest-residen.html] [http://www.buckinghamshireadvertiser.co.uk/south-buckinghamshire-news/local-buckinghamshire-advertiser-news/2010/09/23/one-of-england-s-oldest-woman-marks-110th-birthday-82398-27323388/]
===Esme Pearce=== {{Expand section|date=May 2011}} '''Irene Esme Pearce''' (nÃ©e '''Lovett'''; born 5 January 1901)<ref name="GRG"/> from [[Norwich]] is an English supercentenarian. At the age of {{age|1901|1|5}}, Pearce is the seventh oldest verified person in the United Kingdom following the death of 111-year-old Gladys Good in October 2011 and the oldest verified living person born in the 20th century. [http://www.eveningnews24.co.uk/news/esme_celebrates_109th_birthday_1_486769]
